## Glass in Your Dumplings: Not Just a Crunchy Surprise

This week's food recall reports reveal a concerning pattern. Ajinomoto Foods North America Inc., a repeat offender, has issued recalls for several frozen products, including dumplings and fried rice, due to glass fragments in the food. Glass fragments ranged in size from 1-3 cm long and 2-4 mm wide -- a literal recipe for disaster in terms of consumer safety.

The affected products include items like Ajinomoto Green Gyoza Dumplings and Trader Joe's Vegetable Fried Rice. These products were distributed in flexible retail bags or cartons, intended to be stored frozen and fully cooked before consumption. Yet, the presence of glass calls into question whether the manufacturing standards at Ajinomoto Foods can ensure consumer safety.

## Mustard Oil and Missteps

Mangalm LLC also issued recalls for several pickles such as Tops GOLD Green Chilli Pickle due to potential adulteration with erucic acid from mustard oil. While mustard oil is a common cooking ingredient in some cuisines, high levels of erucic acid can be harmful, suggesting that either ingredient sourcing or testing protocols are insufficient.

## The Persistence of Repeat Offenders

Out of the brands flagged this week, Ajinomoto Foods stands out as it has a history of food safety violations. This raises the question of whether the current oversight mechanisms and consequences for repeat offenders are sufficient to protect consumers. With a total of 52 recalls and 52 Class I violations, CHETAK NEW YORK LLC holds the dubious distinction of being the worst offender, followed by Made Fresh Salads Inc with 16 Class I violations.

## Conclusion

This week underscores the importance of vigilance in monitoring food safety recalls and accountability for brands with repeated violations. Always check the recall list before purchasing and consuming packaged foods, and demand transparency from manufacturers when safety standards fail.
